                type="document" xml:id="d269">
                <head>269. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At 6:35 p.m. on August 3, the President met in the Cabinet Room of the White
                    House with <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_WGEG1"
                        >Wheeler</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">McGeorge
                        Bundy</persName> to discuss Vietnam. (Johnson Library,
                        <persName>Johnson</persName> Daily Diary) No record of the meeting, which
                    lasted until 7:15 p.m., has been found. A telephone conversation between Bundy
                    and <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> at 2:45 p.m.. however, previewed
                    the meeting: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“B called to see if Sec had message re the 6:15. Sec did. Sec said he
                            presumed it was on the Gulf of Tonkin and B said yes. B supposed we
                            would review the rules of engagement. B said we need a draft reply to
                            Max; since we were not asking any staff, could Sec bring whatever he
                            wanted himself. B said he thought this would all pass over. Sec said
                                <persName corresp="#p_Khanh1">Khanh</persName> is kicking up, saying
                            we should retaliate.” (Department of State, Rusk Files: Lot 72 D 192,
                            Telephone Conversations)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The meeting was delayed until 6:35 p.m. because of a reception for American
                    foreign language newspaper editors.</p>
            </div>
